I saw this dandy caribou with a full set of velvet- clad antlers smashing its muzzle and face repeatedly into the ice pack. (Shame the photos couldn't capture the antler detail, grateful that I got any pictures at all.) I later learned about the archeaological significance of these kinds of sites, coupled with this predicatable behaviour in Caribou and Ovis dallii, in the context of the southern Yukon. Caribou seek out ice packs in the summer months to cool themselves down and escape biting insects. We were up on the summit of a ridge to the northwest of High Tuya Lake when we spotted this large, gangly animal loping across 'the dust bowl'. We got some exceptional, distant views without disturbing it. This was my first ever caribou sighting, while appreciating the remoteness of this site, it felt really special. Iirc, this was my 4th lifer mammal of the day, too. Bonkers. 3874063447				http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/	2024-03-15T04:28:54Z		https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/127828569	Wairambar Rainforest					iNaturalist	Observations	iNaturalist research-grade observations		HumanObservation				https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/127828569	127828569		Wairambar Rainforest																								Annual caribou migration, a narrow line of caribou pass by in a matter of hours in early July 1980 Near Yathkyed Lake, Nunavut, Canada. The area is a plain almost entirely treeless , though where there was moving ground water (along faults lines?) a few very low very stunted, very old conifers endured. The area was dotted with small kettle lakes with the last last traces of winter ice. Estimated herd size ~8,000 spread over about 15 km width, would advance as a line for a couple of kilometers then break up for a short time, spread out and feed , repeat , repeat. Once spotted all aircraft were grounded hence the long distance photos. The herd passed almost silently through our tent camp giving it a berth of about 500m. All individuals asked to stay inside tents. Herd did not appear affected or agitated by our presence.															1980-08-06T10:05:00-05:00	10:05:00-05:00						1980/08/06 10:05 AM																CA	Nunavut				Kivalliq Region, NU, Canada												62.7797581952	-96.0190091656	EPSG:4326	5000																																		282297964				Wairambar Rainforest		2022-07-25T12:02:43Z				42199								Rangifer tarandus								Animalia	Chordata	Mammalia	Artiodactyla		Cervidae				Rangifer							species
